<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Open Interest in UK Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Open interest for the
International Petroleum Exchange's (IPE) new natural gas contract
has reached a new record at 6210 lots, according to an
announcement by the IPE here today.
</P>
<P>
This is equivalent to nearly 190 million therms of natural gas,
more than double the daily level of production in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Open interest for natural gas futures has been increasing
steadily since the contract was launched on January 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
The IPE said volumes of trade have also been increasing. So far
this month average daily trading volumes have been more than 330
lots (equivalent to about 10 million therms, or 15 percent of
daily UK production).
</P>
<P>
This compares with an average of 220 lots a day in July. The
contract is attracting increasing interest within the natural gas
industry.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas futures are traded as a monthly strip of daily
deliveries at the National Balancing Point (NBP) within the UK's
National Transmission System.
</P>
<P>
The NBP has emerged as the focus for trading within the UK
natural gas market.
</P>
<P>
Each lot is 1,000 therms a day for an individual month, and
trade is carried out in multiples of five lots.
</P>
<P>
Richard Ward, executive vice president of Business Development
at the IPE, said, "It is clear that the natural gas future
contract is becoming increasingly important to the industry."
</P>
<P>
"We are working very closely with the companies and individuals
to ensure that their risk management needs are met, and we will
continue to develop the contract to take advantage of further
opportunities in the UK and Europe," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
