<HEADLINE> Cuba, China Win on Second Day of Hong Kong Women's Volleyball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Cuba and
runner-up China won their respective matches on the second day at
the the Hong Kong leg of the World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba won over Italy 15-9, 15-6, 15-8 in 59 minutes for its
second win here, while the Chinese team scored its first victory
by beating the Japanese side 15-7, 15-5, 15-11.
</P>
<P>
The high-leaping Cubans proved to be too much for the Italians,
especially when they launched their trade-mark spikes. The
Italians seemed lacking the steam they enjoyed last night when
they beat China 3-2.
</P>
<P>
"The Italians did not play as well as they could. They were
tired today since they fourght a hard match against China
yesterday," said Cuban coach Antonio Perdomo.
</P>
<P>
But the veteran coach declined to predict their match against
China Sunday. He simply said: "That will be very hard."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese did not play well yesterday. They failed to make
very effective attacks in the first two sets, although they
imporved their game later in the match," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Things will change and maybe today they will be better and
tomorrow they are more defferent," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba is the world best even if they have recently changed the
line-up. They jump high and launch powerful smashes which were
hard to block," said Julio Velasco, head coach of the Italian team.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a very good experience to play the best team in
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Velasco admitted that his team played a hard and sensetive
match last night and the team still lacked the skills for
effective receiving.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese fielded an all-veteran line-up in the opening set
against Japan. The set went almost all the Chinese way, except
for the middle part when the Japanese won six points in a row
through the strength of jump serves by Minako Onuri.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese won the two following sets 15-5 and 15-11, also
with flatuations during the latter part of the sets.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Lang Ping said that her players played to
their form tonight. But they failed to launch counter-attacks and
lacked a good coordination in the late stages of the three sets,
when the Japanese launched threatening jump serves to foil Chinese
first setters.
</P>
<P>
"This is anyway only the fifth game for the new Chinese
team. The new players have not confronted themselves with many
strong sides," Lang explained.
</P>
<P>
The spiker-turned coach said that she would, as in the matches
played so far, field some newcomers Sunday. "I have only six
veterans in the team. How can I ignore the new ones, especially
when they need to obtain experience through competitions of this
caliber," she said.
</P>
<P>
She declined to predict the eventual winners of the three-day
event. "I have never done so, even before or during the Olympic
Games," she dais.
</P>
<P>
"I have always asked my players to be really serious and give
their best shots, no matter what team they are to play," Lang
added.
</P>
<P>
The top three teams from the five legs of this year's Grand
Prix join host Japan in the finals set for August 29-31 in Kobe,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
In the Taipei leg of the Grand Prix earlier Saturday, Russia
won its second match by beating South Korea 15-5, 15-9, 15-8 while
the Netherlands scored their first win by downing the United
States 15-2, 15-12, 15-5.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, South Korea beat the United States 15-4, 15-4, 15-4
and Russia downed the Netherlands 15-0, 16-14, 15-2.
</P>
<P>
On the leg's final day on Sunday, South Korea takes on the
Netherlands and the United States will play Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
