<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Commences Talks With IMF Over Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi today said that the Kenyan government had opened up
discussions with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the
suspended 215 million U.S. Dollars loan to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a fund-raising occasion, Mudavadi said
that the government was ready to fulfil tough conditions imposed
by IMF and expressed optimism that the talks would be successful.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Kenya had made a lot of progress in such
areas as liberalization of the economy, privatization of
state-owned companies and retrenchment of the civil service where
the IMF had raised concern.
</P>
<P>
Micah Cheserem, Governor of the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK),
said yesterday that the government was ready to resume "tough
negotiations" with the IMF over the lapse of the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is considering re-opening talks with IMF
for the remaining two-year arrangement of the loan agreed in
April last year between the Kenyan government and IMF, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based IMF suspended on July 31 its key loan to
Kenya, citing high-level corruption in Kenya's government
departments as the main reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
