<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Blames Turkish Cypriot Leader for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today blamed Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash for the
collapse of their negotiations on the Cyprus problem held in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival here from the U.N.-led talks, Clerides said it is
generally accepted by the U.N. and all those envoys monitoring the
Glion direct talks that Denktash is exclusively at fault for the
failure of the five-day talks which ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Denktash did not go there to negotiate, but to try to impede
our course towards Europe," he said, adding "this did not succeed."
</P>
<P>
Denktash has threatened to finalize Cyprus' partition of Cyprus
if the European Union (EU) will go ahead with its planned
accession talks with Cyprus scheduled for early next year, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The threats are doomed to fail because the EU will not change
its decisions, the president asserted.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that Denktash's recalcitrant tactics at the
talks have elicited "strong international reaction."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the conviction that the U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor for the Cyprus problem, Diego Cordovez, will
"call things by their true name" in his report to the
U.N. Security Council next Wednesday and will apportion blame for
the failure of the talks where it is due.
</P>
<P>
The president said that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will
work to set up another face-to-face meeting between the two
leaders, but he reiterated he would not attend such a meeting if
Denktash refuses to discuss substantial aspects of the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Clerides also left the door open for further meetings between
himself and Denktash in Cyprus to discuss humanitarian issues,
saying that they "may still be possible."
</P>
<P>
Last month, the two communities' leaders had two meetings
in Nicosia, under the auspices of the U.N. Resident
Representative Gustave Feissel, and reached an agreement on
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
The two meetings followed the first round of direct talks
between them, held from July 9 to 12, at Troutbeck, near New
York.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took
over the northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite this island nation as bi-communal and
bi-zonal federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
