<HEADLINE> Arafat Again Blasts Israel's Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat today repeated his condemnation of the Israeli sanctions
against the Palestinian people, imposed after the suicide bombing
attack on July 30 in Jerusalem, which killed 16 people.
</P>
<P>
In an open meeting with Palestinian journalists, academics,
university officials and teachers in the headquarters of the
Nablus Municipality, Arafat spoke about various topics on the
latest political developments, according to a report of JMCC, an
East Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service.
</P>
<P>
He declared that the Palestinians reject Israel's request for
increasing efforts to counter terror against Israel. "We reject
all efforts to impose conditions or dictate to us," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the act by Israel to hold up monetary transfers
owed to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is nothing short
of an attempt to steal tax money belonging to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's statement coincided with a Washington report that the
U.S. has openly voiced its disappointment at Israel's delay in
releasing funds to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with domestic problems, Arafat stressed the importance
of the media, saying that it should do its best to enhance the
national ideal of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader encouraged the media to represent the
conscience of a struggling people by sharpening their pens for the
battle. He also asked the academics to form a national committee
to document the history of Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
