<HEADLINE> Calm Back to Comoros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A special envoy from Comoros
said today that calm had been back to Comoros and negotiations
between the cessationists and the government were on course.
</P>
<P>
Unrest arised on August 3 when secessionists of Anjouan, the
second island of the Comoros, demanded a return to French rule
and the Comoran government later sent troops to quell the
secessionists revolt.
</P>
<P>
The Comoran special envoy, Abdou Bakari Boina, today delivered
a special message to Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka from
Comoros President Abdul Karim Taki.
</P>
<P>
Bakari Boina told reporters that the present crisis in the
islands was partly a creation of the international press.
</P>
<P>
He refuted news reports that a four-man delegation sent by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) to the islands was abducted
by government soldiers early this week.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he pointed out, the OAU delegation led by Pierre Yere
from Cote d'Ivoire was being escorted and provided with security
by his government.
</P>
<P>
Bakari Boina is expected to deliver similar special messages
to the governments of Tanzania, Mozambique and South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
