<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rybkin on Upcoming Yeltsin-Maskhadov Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov are to held a meeting in
Moscow Monday and to sign a document to follow up on earlier
agreements, Russian Security Council Secretary Ivan Rybkin said
here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, Rybkin today had talks
with Chechen First Prime Minister Movladi Udugov, who arrived in
Moscow today with a Chechen delegation, that led up to the signing
of a protocol of the upcoming summit.
</P>
<P>
It took a long time to weigh the date and place for the two
presidents' meeting.
</P>
<P>
In a move to "put an end to all unwanted comments on the
upcoming meeting of the presidents," Udugov said both sides agreed
that the meeting should be held in Moscow and Maskhadov approved
of their choice.
</P>
<P>
On the question of hostages, the Russian and foreign hostages
kidnapped in Chechnya totaled 14 as of recent days. Both Rybkin
and Udugov agreed to sign a protocol on the issue Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The protocol will include a provision that the relatives of
those missing, killed or abducted, will be appointed members of
the commission dealing with these issues. They will be allowed to
conduct the search in any part of Chechnya or Russia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to economic problems, Rybkin noted that the amount of
funds transferred to Chechnya since the beginning of this year has
reached 847 billion roubles (about 148 million US dollars). This
is the first time this figure has been publicly announced, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin also said that the federal government plans to transfer
120 billion roubles (about 21 million US dollars ) to Chechnya
monthly. Besides, it will also finance the repairs on the oil
pipeline passing through Chechnya and its protection.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Udugov quoted Maskhadov as saying that Chechnya
should be able to rebuild its economy on its own.
</P>
<P>
But, at the same time the Chechen government has given Moscow a
plan of economic restoration, which, Udugov hopes, could help
improve the economic situation in the republic faster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
