<HEADLINE> Tajik Government Troops to Take Offensive to Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tajik government is sending
more troops to the Shaartuz and Kabodien districts in the south of
the country where the rebel brigade of Colonel Makhmud
Khudoiberdyev and his armed supporters had moved in Friday night.
</P>
<P>
According to an Itar-Tass news agency report from Dushanbe,
Tajikistan, Tajik government troops are getting ready for a
large-scale offensive to destroy the last pocket of resistance.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass quoted a high-placed source in one of the power
ministries as saying Khudoiberdyev has neither means nor chances
to put up long resistance.
</P>
<P>
The source believes that the only wise thing for him to do is
to lay down arms and stop armed confrontation. Otherwise, all
responsibility for the consequences will lie on the mutinous
colonel and all those who support his adventurist and foolhardy
plans.
</P>
<P>
Another report said that U.S. Permanent Representative to the
United Nations Bill Richardson arrived in Dushanbe today to
familiarize himself with the settlement process in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
According to Richardson, the U.N. Security Council and U.S.
President Bill Clinton want to know what help is needed to
facilitate this process.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day stay in the capital the U.S. representative
is expected to talk with Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov and
Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Tajik government forces took full control of
most of southern Tajikistan, except the Shaartuz and Kabodien
districts, which Khudoiberdyev's brigade and armed supporters are
based on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
