<HEADLINE> Clinton Suggests Parents Get Early Preparation for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today suggested parents take advantage of higher education
programs just signed into law as part of the balanced-budget
package to begin preparing for their children's college education.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address today, Clinton said parents should
get early preparation for college when their children reach the
sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
He also announced a campaign by the Department of Education to
inform people about the new tax breaks that will become available
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Among the tax incentives included in the new five-year balanced
budget law are the Hope scholarships, a tax credit of up to 1,500
U.S. dollars to help cover the first two years of college, an
additional 10,000 dollar tax break for some families, and a new
life-time learning credit aimed at college juniors, seniors,
graduate students and adults wanting to enhence their skills.
</P>
<P>
Parents and grandparents can also withdraw money from their
Individual Retirement Accounts (IRA), beginning this January,
without penalty to pay for higher education expenses.
</P>
<P>
They can also open new education IRAs, in which they can
invest 500 dollars per child every year to build up money
tax-free for college.
</P>
<P>
The program also includes the largest increase in Pell grants
in 20 years and gives scholarships to about 350,000 more
students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
