<HEADLINE> Disappeared S. Leonean FM Back in Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Pallo Bangura, Foreign Minister of
Sierra Leone's military government, who disappeared after the
failed Abidjan peace talks at the end of July, has resurfaced in
the capital Freetown, saying that he has gone for "quiet diplomacy".
</P>
<P>
"Now I'm alive, I've not been kidnapped, not been killed and
I'm back in Sierra Leone," he was quoted by the British Broadcasting
Company today.
</P>
<P>
Bangura denied that he had quarreled with the junta and quit
from the military government.
</P>
<P>
"I'am back in Sierra Leone and continuing with my job," he
said.
</P>
<P>
As for what he has been doing during the last two weeks,
Bangura said he was carrying out "what is in my own style, that
is quiet diplomacy", which "the people who should know, the head
of state knew."
</P>
<P>
According to the foreign minister, his quiet diplomatic
mission "was very successful and we are now looking forward to a
positive next step".
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to progress in the sense of dealing
with the crisis in Sierra Leone which we want to see successfully
settled," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bangura refused to comment on the recent meeting of west
African foreign ministers in Accra, Ghana, which insisted on the
reinstatement of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and more
sanctions against Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"When they do get in touch with us, we will respond
appropriately," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangura headed the junta delegation last month to Abidjan,
Cote d'Ivoire, to attend talks with west African countries'
foreign ministers for final settlement of the crisis in his
country.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Bangura and senior diplomat Dauda Kamara
met with Cote d'Ivoire's Foreign Minister Amara Essy on August 1
and did not return to the luxury hotel where the delegation
lodged.
</P>
<P>
Speculations went around that he might have been hijacked,
kidnapped, killed or even gone to seek political asylum in
Ethiopia, where he had served in the Sierra Leonean Embassy,
while Karmara could have sought refuge in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Bangura's wife had criticized him
vehemently for associating himself with the junta.
</P>
<P>
However, Bangura denied such family quarrel, saying he had
dealt with the question at a press conference he gave in Freetown
at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"I hope I have dealt with it definitively," he said, adding
that instead of trying to persuade him to quit the government,
his wife should receive the fact that he had taken the job.
</P>
<P>
Bangura was pride of his job as foreign minister of the junta,
saying it gave him an opportunity to pursue the peace process and
seek progress, development and democracy in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
