<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Win Women's World Volleyball Grand Prix in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champions Cuba
defeated runners-up China 3-1 and claimed the title with three
straight victories at the three-day Hong Kong leg of the World
Women's Volleyball Grand Prix here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba, who had earlier defeated Japan and Italy in straight
sets, outplayed China 16-14, 15-11, 8-15, 15-7.
</P>
<P>
Italy came to the second place with two wins against one loss,
China ranked third with two losses and one win and winless Japan
was fourth and last.
</P>
<P>
After finishing second and third in the Macao and Hong Kong
legs, China failed to reach the finals.
</P>
<P>
"With the cancellation of the Jakarta leg, we have had one less
leg to play. That cost a lot on us," Chinese head coach Lang Ping
 said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that China failed to make the finals in
the history of the World Volleyball Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
In the first match here Sunday afternoon, Italy beat Japan
15-2, 15-10, 15-6. It was their first victory over Japan in any
official competition.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese fielded an all-veteran line-up in the opening set
against Cuba, and improved their defense. But the Cubans took the
set 16-14 anyway.
</P>
<P>
The Cubans pulled away after the two sides tied 7-7 in the
second set and, by gradually widening the gap, took the second
15-11.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pulled one set back in the third, where they almost
led all the way through to a 15-8 win after a 1-1 early tie.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese came to lead at 3-1 in the fourth, but that did not
last long as the Cubans fought back with more effective and
accurate spikes. Chinese defense was greatly foiled. The Cubans
took the set 15-7 and the match.
</P>
<P>
"This match is very important to both of us. If we lose, we'd
have little chance to go to the finals," said Cuban head coach
Antonio Perdomo.
</P>
<P>
The veteran coach admitted his team was greatly pressed during
the first two sets.
</P>
<P>
Very happy with his team though, he said that he would be most
happy if China entered the finals. "We really wish to play China
in the finals," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's head coach Lang Ping said that her players had played
to their form. "But they had some problem dealing the crucial
moment, too eager to crush the opponents by spiking," she said.
</P>
<P>
"They need more time for psychological training and
experience," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Our team really didn't have enough time to get ready for this
Grand Prix competition, frankly speaking, just one month after the
 new team was formed," she explained.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team would well learn from Grand Prix matches and
get themselves ready for the week-long Asian volleyball
championships set to start on September 21 in Manila, Lang said.
</P>
<P>
In the Grand prix Taipei leg which closed Sunday, South Korea
beat the Netherlands 15-7, 15-3, 15-5 and Russia downed the United
States 17-15, 15-4, 15-2 in the final two matches.
</P>
<P>
Russia took the first place with three straight wins, South
Korea was second with two wins against one loss, the Netherlands
finished third with one win and two losses and winless Americans
were fourth and last.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Prix has five legs for the preliminary stage. After
Macao, Seoul, Hong Kong and Taipei, only one leg remains, which is
the Gifu event on August 22-24, with Russia, United States, Cuba
and Japan participating.
</P>
<P>
The top three out of the eight participating teams in the
preliminary stage will join hosts Japan in the finals set for
August 29-31 in Kobe, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
