<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, August 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's Defense Agency plans to send a main battle
fighter jet force equipped with F-15 jet fighters abroad for a
multinational war game and inflight refueling training next year,
the Tokyo Shimbun reported today.
</P>
<P>
The war game, which will involve U.S., British and Canadian air
forces, will be held in Alaska, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo Shimbun said it will be unprecedented for Japan's Air
Self-Defense Force to participate in a military exercise and
inflight refueling training abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Agency will make a decision on the plan at an
agency meeting scheduled for August 20, according to the Tokyo
Shimbun.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia and the breakaway Republic of Chechnya signed
here today a protocol on creating a joint search commission
dealing with hostages in Chechnya, according to the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Secretary of the Russian Security
Council Ivan Rybkin and First Vice-Premier of the Chechen
government Movladi Udugov, who arrived in Moscow Saturday with a
Chechen delegation.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin told reporters that the protocol includes the relatives
of those missing, killed or forcibly detained in Chechnya into the
joint search commission and that they would be granted unimpeded
access to all places on the territory of the Russian Federation
and the Chechen Republic.
</P>
<P>
A total of 14 Russian and foreign hostages, mostly journalists,
have been reportedly kidnaped or detained in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the Russian media reported that two members of the
VID television company working for the "Outlook" program broadcast
by ORT television have been released in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A U.S. Navy helicopter crashed in the northern
Gulf Saturday but all four crew members were rescued, a radio in
the United Arab Emirates reported today.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter crashed at approximately 2:30 p.m. local time
(1130GMT) in international waters in the northern Arabian Gulf
when it was conducting routine operations, the UAE's Capital Radio
quoted a statement by the U.S. Naval Central Command in the Gulf
as saying.
</P>
<P>
All four crew members aboard were rescued after the crash with
one of them being treated for minor injuries, the statement
said. An investigation into the cause of the crash was under way.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chief peace negotiator of the Palestinian National
Authority Saeb Erakat today called on Israel to respect all
agreements between the two sides on which the Mideast peace march
was based.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Voice of Arabs radio, the
Palestinian official said the peace process is "indivisible" and
the ball is now in the Israeli court.
</P>
<P>
He held Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu responsible
for the current peace crisis, which began as Israel broke ground
for the building of a controversial Jewish settlement in
traditional Arab East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as
their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Erakat's statement concurred with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat's sounding demanded that the final settlement talks between
Israel and the Palestinians must run parallel to the
implementation of all agreements reached during the transitional
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
