<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14.7 million US Dollars Paid to HK Traffic Accident Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Social Welfare
Department paid out over 115 million HK dollars (14.7 million
U.S. dollars) in the 1995-1996 financial year to help traffic
accident victims or their dependents.
</P>
<P>
The payment came from the department's Traffic Accident Victims
Assistance (TAVA) Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1995-1996 TAVA Fund annual report, a total of
5,868 applications were received during the period, compared with
5,740 in the previous year, representing an increase of 2.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, police figures showed that there was a 1.9 percent
decrease in the number of traffic casualties, from 20,357 in the
1994-1995 to 19,972 in the year reported.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in application rate indicates that more people
are aware of their right to apply for assistance in the event of
traffic accidents," a department spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The largest payment of the year amounting to 113,901 HK dollars
(14,603 U.S. dollars) was granted to the dependents of a man who
was knocked down by a taxi on April 18, 1995 and subsequently died
three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
The department handled 38 cases of serious traffic accidents
involving heavy casualties during the period.
</P>
<P>
The accident resulting in the largest number of victims
occurred on May 24, 1995 when a coach collided with two lorries,
in which 57 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that the TAVA scheme was designed to
provide speedy financial assistance to victims or their
dependents.
</P>
<P>
Applications for assistance, either in person or by post,
should be made within six months of the traffic accident which
must have been reported to the police.  
</P>
</TEXT>
