<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Plans to Send War Planes Abroad for War Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Defense Agency plans to
send a main battle fighter jet force equipped with F-15 jet
fighters abroad for a multinational war game and inflight
refueling training next year, the Tokyo Shimbun reported today.
</P>
<P>
The war game, which will involve U.S., British and Canadian air
forces, will be held in Alaska, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo Shimbun said it will be unprecedented for Japan's Air
Self-Defense Force to participate in a military exercise and
inflight refueling training abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Agency will make a decision on the plan at an
agency meeting scheduled for August 20, according to the Tokyo
Shimbun.
</P>
<P>
The United States started the multinational military exercise
in 1991, in the form of actual combat. The exercise is held four
times a year.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Air Self-Defense Force started to dispatch
researchers to watch the exercise in 1992. In 1996, Japan for the
first time sent two C-130 transport planes and surface-to-air
missiles to participate in the exercise. On June 9-20, The
Japanese Air Self-Defense Force participated in the exercise in
the same scale.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Shimbun commented that as a country pursuing a
national policy of pure defense, Japan has always been strict in
sending war planes abroad. On inflight refueling training, former
Japanese prime minister Kakuei Tanaka pointed out in 1973 that
"Japan does not possess inflight refueling planes, nor does it
participate in inflight training or exercise."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that in relation to efforts between the
United States and Japan to review their defense cooperation
guidelines, the Japanese Defense Agency's plan to send war planes
to participate a military exercise abroad is a noteworthy
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
