<HEADLINE> Indian Diplomat Sees Bright Prospects for Indo- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Bangladesh
and India will be further enhanced if both sides maintain an
attitude of seeking solution to problems in a spirit of mutual
accommodation, said an Indian diplomat here.
</P>
<P>
"The relationship between the two countries requires careful
and considerate management," Deb Mukherjee, Indian High
Commissioner to Bangladesh, told a press conference this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Mukherjee said that his government has repeatedly said that it
attaches highest importance to relations with Bangladesh and he
saw "bright" prospects for expansion of the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the Ganges water sharing treaty signed last
December, Mukherjee said that leaders of the two countries
exhibited political will in resolving the question, adding that it
shows that most issues can be resolved satisfactorily if the will
to resolve them is present.
</P>
<P>
Besides the water sharing problems involving a total of 54
common rivers, both countries also face a series of disputes such
as cross-border insurgency, smuggling and boundary line
delimitation.
</P>
<P>
Mukherjee also referred to economic issues and said economic
liberalization in both countries has opened up new opportunities
to liberate potentials of their peoples.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned the exchange at various government and private
levels between the two countries and said contacts are enhanced by
the presence of many Bangladeshi students in India and many
nationals from here seeking medical treatment in India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
