<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Set to Earn 18 Billion US Dollars from Export in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has set a goal to earn
18 billion US dollars from exports in the year 2000, or a rise of
33.3 percent over the 13.5 billion dollars the municipality
registered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a development program released recently, the trade
volume of China's financial and commercial center is expected to
reach 38 billion dollars by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The city's foreign trade witnessed its fastest-growing period
in the past five years. The export volume in the period averaged
8.8 billion dollars with an annual increase of 18.2 percent, while
its annual import volume hit 6.8 billion dollars, posting an
average rise of 31.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goals, Shanghai's trading authorities have
formulated concrete plans. By 2000, the city is slated to increase
the number of commodities which can earn more than 50 million
dollars a year from the current 60 items to 100.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume earned from technology and trading services is
expected to be increased to a combined volume of 12 billion
dollars by then. Efforts will also be made to spread the sales
networks and foster more trading agents.
</P>
<P>
The target markets will be diversified; in addition to the
traditional marketplaces, such as Japan, the United States and the
European community, efforts will be paid to tap new emerging
economies in southeast Asia, Oceania, Latin America, the Middle
East and Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
Incentives will be offered for the development of large trading
groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
