<HEADLINE> Russia, Chechnya Sign Protocol on Searching Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the breakaway Republic
of Chechnya signed here today a protocol on creating a joint
search commission dealing with hostages in Chechnya, according to
the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Secretary of the Russian Security
Council Ivan Rybkin and First Vice-Premier of the Chechen
government Movladi Udugov, who arrived in Moscow Saturday with a
Chechen delegation.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin told reporters that the protocol includes the relatives
of those missing, killed or forcibly detained in Chechnya into the
joint search commission and that they would be granted unimpeded
access to all places on the territory of the Russian Federation
and the Chechen Republic.
</P>
<P>
Udugov, for his part, pointed out that the safety of commission
members on the territory of Chechnya would be ensured by the
Interior Ministry, whose head, Kazbek Makhashev, is chairman of
the state search commission under the Chechen president.
</P>
<P>
The Chechen official said that another protocol had been signed
today pertaining to the forthcoming visit of the Chechen president
to Moscow and that an entire range of technical issues pertaining
to the forthcoming presidents' meeting had been discussed.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov are to meet in Moscow on Monday to discuss the whole
range of problems between the Federal Russian and Chechen
authorities, in particular the power-sharing treaty.
</P>
<P>
For the Russian authorities, the problem of hostages kidnaped
in Chechnya is one of the most sensitive problems. It requested
that this issue be settled by Chechnya prior to the forthcoming
Yeltsin-Maskhadov meeting.
</P>
<P>
A total of 14 Russian and foreign hostages, mostly journalists,
have been reportedly kidnaped or detained in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the Russian media reported that two members of the
VID television company working for the "Outlook" program broadcast
by ORT television have been released in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The two journalists -- Ilyas Bogatyrev and Vladislav Chernyayev
-- were released after joint efforts made by the Russian Security
Council, the Federal Security Service, the Russian Interior
Ministry and law endorsement bodies of the Chechen republic.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the two released men are expected to
arrive in Moscow tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
