<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Attracts Growing Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chongqing, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A rapidly increasing number of
people are flocking to the Three Gorges areas along the Yangtze
River to marvel at the natural wonder -- before the river is
dammed up by the year end as part of a multi-million construction
project.
</P>
<P>
Some 114,000 people from home and abroad toured the area
between January and June this year, a figure representing a 38
percent rise over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
While tourism companies report booming business, enthusiastic
tourists, however, are frustrated by the difficulty in securing
seats at touring ships.
</P>
<P>
As the peak season usually comes in September and October, the
number of tourists to the Three-Gorge region is expected to hit a
record high this year, according to the industry's analysis.
</P>
<P>
One reason for the increase is the fear that the dam-up of the
river in the region within the year might more or less damage the
Three-Gorges' natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
Tourism authorities have worked hard to dispel such groundless
anticipation, assuring repeatedly that with good preservation,
tourists will enjoy no less of nature's beauty, but more of
quality service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds Another Hydro-power Project in Border Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government recently
officially approved the construction of another large hydro-power
project in Lancang River in southwest China's Yunnan Province
bordering Myanmar and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Dachaoshan Power Plant, located in the middle reaches of the
Lancang River, is designed to have an installed capacity of 1.35
million kw. The power generating capacity is set to reach 5.9
billion kwh annually in its initial period of operation, and
eventually hit seven billion kwh a year.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 8.9 billion yuan, the first generating
unit of the plant is scheduled to be operational in 2001. All the
six units are expected to be in full operation in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The site of the project, with a steep water drop and sparse
population, is ideal for such a large project.
</P>
<P>
The Dachaoshan Hydro-power Co. Ltd. was the sole developer and
future operator of the project, which is jointly funded by State
Development and Investment Corporation, Yunnan Hongta Industrial
Co. Ltd., Yunnan Electricity Corporation and Yunnan Development
and Investment Corporation,
</P>
<P>
Up to now, some 1.2 billion yuan has been allotted for the
preparation of the project. Water diversion tunnels, key to the
damming of the river, have been put in use since May of 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
