<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shareholding System A Lifesaver for China's State-Owned Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A shareholding system is an
essential and feasible means of reforming the state-owned economy
and will lead to a breakthrough in the decade-long reform of
China's economic system.
</P>
<P>
This view is shared by Chinese economists and officials in an
ongoing media discussion.
</P>
<P>
They held that most of the large- and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises in China, which at present are solely state-owned, may
be transformed into shareholding companies in the future.
</P>
<P>
A shareholding system is an ideal way to realize public
ownership, according to some economists, and is needed to further
boost the Chinese economy, which is still in the primary stage of
socialism.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy (SCRE) show that the 100 state-owned ventures selected to
try out the modern enterprise system through shareholding
transformation have seen their total assets grow 99.45 billion
yuan, or some 27.6 percent over 1994, to more than 360 billion
yuan at the end of last year -- a laudable accomplishment when
compared with the general inertia of the state sector.
</P>
<P>
At the root of the poor performance of state ventures is the
"state-ownership" of their assets -- an abstractly defined
practice which doesn't fall in step with the socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, transforming these businesses into shareholding
companies will prove to be the wisest way to lead them out of
financial dilemma, said economist Wei Jie in a recent article in
China Securities.
</P>
<P>
Yang Qixian, vice-chairman of the Chinese Economy Restructuring
Research Society, echoed Wei's view by saying that a shareholding
economy will help create clear enterprise ownerships and prompt
the enterprises to be more market-oriented rather than responsive
only to government departments.
</P>
<P>
China piloted the practice of transforming state ventures into
shareholding companies in 1984. More enterprises joined the
program in 1991, but the number of shareholding companies which
evolved from former state ventures has hovered around 9,000 since
1995.
</P>
<P>
The shareholding system was unable to come into its own, since
people still tended to believe that sole state ownership was the
only way to establish public ownership.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin resolved the debate in late May in a
speech at the Party School of the CPC Central Committee, which is
said to have mapped out the course of state sector reform.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called for bold exploration of new ways to achieve public
ownership that may substantially boost the overall economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's top state economic officials also
showed increasing determination to transform the state-owned
enterprises into shareholding companies.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji stressed during an inspection tour of
the state-owned enterprises in northeastern Liaoning Province in July
that the Chinese stock market may become an important source of
funding for the state ventures, as it is gliding along a steady
and standardized development course.
</P>
<P>
The economists reached consensus on the relationship between a
shareholding system and public ownership, saying that changing
state-owned enterprises into shareholding companies only adjusts
the mangement mode of the state enterprises and has nothing to do
with privatization.
</P>
<P>
And some economists noted that a shareholding system could only
embolden instead of weakening the leading position of public
ownership in the Chinese economy, since it allows the state to
control a shareholding enterprise by holding 51 percent of its
stake, and will thereby increase the influence of the state assets
to a greater extent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Launch Environment Project for Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will launch a project
of 1.7 million Kuwait dinars (5.61 million U.S. dollars) to green
sandy areas in the country in preparation for a regional summit
scheduled for December.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Mohsen Al-Qallaf, a senior official at the Public
Authority for Agricultural Affairs said the project would be
carried out by a local firm in September and be completed by the
time of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) summit.
</P>
<P>
He said the project, which will be in three stages, would
include planting seasonal flowers and small trees in various areas
of the country, in addition to turning sandy areas into green
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
The summit will bring together leaders of Kuwait, Saudi
Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates and Oman to
discuss various issues facing the GCC countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
