<HEADLINE> Five African Leaders Calls for Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Libya, Burkina
Faso, Chad, Mali and Niger have called for redoubling efforts to
find solutions to some African issues, including development and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The leaders issued the call in their joint statement which was
issued at the close of their summit meeting Saturday night in the
Libyan capital of Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which was published by Libya's news agency
JANA, underlined the necessity of enhancing the rapprochement
among African nations as a step toward achieving African unity.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that leaders of the five African states
commissioned their foreign ministers to hold a meeting in Tripoli
next month to consider this issue.
</P>
<P>
About Libya's dispute with some Western powers, the statement
said that leaders of the five African states expressed their
anxiety about the continuation of the U.N. sanctions imposed on
Libya, which have negative effects on Libya and the economies of
the five African states.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the five states also made an urgent appeal to
the international community to find a fair and ultimate solution
to Libya's dispute with both the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
They called on U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to send a
fact-finding commission to Libya to see how U.N. sanctions are
affecting the Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for refusing to
turn over two Libyans charged in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet
over Lockerbie, Scotland which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The five-nation African summit opened in Tripoli
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
