<HEADLINE> Nigerians Accused of Planting Land Mines in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
Sierra Leone today accused Nigerian troops based near the
capital's international airport of "planting land-mines" in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The troops have been based at the airport for the past two and
a half months after the May 25 coup which ousted the civilian
government of Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement broadcast on state radio, "a tank
belonging to the Nigerian army was blown up on Friday, killing at
least 15 Nigerian soldiers."
</P>
<P>
The tank, the radio said, ran over the mines by mistake and
detonated them which have been planted to trap or forestall
attacks from Sierra Leone soldiers stationed about two miles
away.
</P>
<P>
The radio also expressed "concern over the use of the airport
by Nigerian soldiers as a base to transfer hard drugs including
cocaine to Europe and South America."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three Sierra Leone soldiers were seriously injured
on Saturday after their vehicle was shot at by Nigerian troops
manning a checkpoint at Jui, about 13 miles from the capital.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, one corporal and two lance corporals, were among
a group of eight soldiers on their way to the military training
center at Benguema, 20 miles east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
They were taken to the Benguema military hospital for
emergency surgery and then flown to the capital by military
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed at the hospital, the commanding officer at
Benguema, Anthony Kargbo accused the Nigerians of "itching for a
fight. This is a real provocation. Why should they halt our
vehicle to search for arms in our own land?"
</P>
<P>
This reporter drove some 200 yards from the military vehicle
and heard a volley of shots ring out in quick succession after a
Nigerian soldier ordered the car to stop to be searched for arms.
</P>
<P>
The car sped away and the shots shattered its rear windscreen.
</P>
<P>
The incident immediately brought dozens of heavily armed rebel
combatants and Sierra Leone soldiers out of their trenches about
a mile way from the Nigerian base.
</P>
<P>
They shouted in a frenzy mood, threatening to kill anybody as
they brandish their AK47s. There has not been any report of
clashes so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
