<HEADLINE> Lissouba Pays Surprise Visit to Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 17 (Xinhuaba) -- Congolese President Pascal
Lissouba crossed the Congo River Saturday to make a surprise
visit to Democratic Congo (K) and explained to President Laurent
Kabila why the exchange of shell fire between the two capitals
broke out.
</P>
<P>
A report from Kinshasa said Lissouba has blamed the initial
shelling from Brazzaville, over the river to Kinshasa, on his
predecessor and rival Denis Sassou Nguesso. A bloody conflict
between their rival forces has killed hundreds in Brazzaville
since June.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know where the shells came from," Kabila said on
state television late on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I've just spoken about it with my counterpart. It seems that
they came from the other side, from Sassou Nguesso's fighters...
We're going to find out where they came from."
</P>
<P>
Speaking also on Kinshasa television, Lissouba accused Sassou
of recruiting African mercenaries to foment trouble.
</P>
<P>
"I promised Kabila to bring evidence that his opponents,
Rwandans who were responsible for the genocide in Rwanda, Ugandan
opponents as well as Central African Republic mutineers, are
being recruited by this man," Lissouba said after Saturday's
talks.
</P>
<P>
"I think he wants to set fire to and shed blood in central
Africa," Lissouba charged.
</P>
<P>
Presidential elections in Congo (B) were postponed because of
the fighting between the two would-be candidates.
</P>
<P>
Renewed fighting in Brazzaville has forced thousands of people
to flee the capital over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks have stalled in the Gabonese capital of
Libreville, but are expected to resume on Monday, diplomats were
quoted as having said.
</P>
<P>
Lissouba conceded that the talks were getting bogged down, and
suggested that the mediation efforts of U.N. special envoy
Mohamed Sahnoun might not be able to take them further.
</P>
<P>
However, he appealed for a regional solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has backed the idea of an African
peace-keeping force but wants a real end to hostilities before it
is sent in.
</P>
<P>
Lissouba also said he would ask neighboring central African
countries to provide monitors when the presidential election was
finally held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
