<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Honor Agreements with Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief peace negotiator of the
Palestinian National Authority Saeb Erakat today called on Israel
to respect all agreements between the two sides on which the
Mideast peace march was based.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Voice of Arabs radio, the
Palestinian official said the peace process is "indivisible" and
the ball is now in the Israeli court.
</P>
<P>
He held Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu responsible
for the current peace crisis, which began as Israel broke ground
for the building of a controversial Jewish settlement in
traditional Arab East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as
their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Erakat's statement concurred with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat's sounding demanded that the final settlement talks between
Israel and the Palestinians must run parallel to the
implementation of all agreements reached during the transitional
period.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of resuming peace negotiations now that the
Palestinian-Israeli security coordination has been restored,
Erakat said there are still deep differences regarding security
issues.
</P>
<P>
The PNA said Friday it planned to match Israeli sanctions with
a selective and gradual boycott of Israeli goods. It also called
for national unity talks with opponents of Palestinian-Israeli
peace deals.
</P>
<P>
Arafat condemned as collective punishment Israeli sanctions and
its closure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip following the July 30
twin suicide bombing in Jerusalem, saying they would only weaken
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman Marwan Kanfani met Friday night with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on Egypt's ongoing efforts to
revive the faltering Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation Friday, President Hosni Mubarak's
political advisor Osama el-Baz and Arafat reviewed the situation
in the region after U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross' mediation
between Israel and the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
