<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Generators Installed in China's Large Hydro-power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A power generating unit with a
capacity of 550,000 kw was today installed in Ertan Hydro-power
Plant, China's second largest hydro-power project next to the
Three Gorges endeavor.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Junfeng, general manager of Ertan Hydro-power
Development Corporation, the project, located in the middle
reaches of Yalong River in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
will sport six generating units with a combined capacity of 3.3
million kw. The plant is set to generate 17 billion kwh of
electricity annually after it becomes fully operational in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the newly installed unit, along with another one to be
installed later, were expected to be put in use next July.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a 240-meter-high dike is now underway. Upon
completion, the new 101-square-km reservoir is to hold 5.8 billion
cubic meters of water.
</P>
<P>
After operation of its first unit, Ertan is slated to transmit
electricity to the outside networks in October of 1998. "After
that, one unit will be put into production every four months," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
The project is set to become one of the key energy supply bases
in southwest China upon its completion in 2000, lessening the
tight electricity supply in the region.
</P>
<P>
Liu also revealed that his company is to further tap the
abundant hydro-power resources in other parts of the Yalong
River. The preparatory studies on two new projects, with
respective designed capacities of 1.8 million kw and 440,000 kw,
are now underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
