<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Use of Foreign Experts Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province invites more than 5,000 foreign technological experts to
work there every year, giving a strong push to local economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The province has given priority to its agricultural
development, introducing many fine crop breeds and technology with
which it has established a number of production bases for fruit,
vegetables and aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
With the help of overseas experts, the province has raised its
paddy output by 350 million kg. since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong also stresses that the practice of using overseas
experts should aid the development of large-scale state-owned
enterprises and key projects.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the province has completed
technological improvements on over 400 projects and has helped a
number of enterprises extricate themselves from financial troubles
with the assistance of foreign experts.
</P>
<P>
Liang Zhuocheng, director of the Provincial Bureau of Foreign
Experts Affairs, said that the use of foreign experts has turned
from a mandatory practice into a voluntary one.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of villages and towns in Dongguan, a city in the Pearl
River Delta, have more than 100 enterprises each that were set up
through the introduction of foreign experts and technology.
</P>
<P>
The use of experts has extended to the less-developed northern
and western part of the province, said officials here, adding that
the trend is sure to invigorate Guangdong's economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
