<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Enact National Policy on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government may enact
the national policy on acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS)
before the end of the year, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said four technical committees had prepared the
draft policy in 1995, but the National Council on Health has
failed to enact it for twice.
</P>
<P>
With the recent death of AIDS complications of Fela
Anikulapo-Kuti, Nigeria's pop music star known as Afro-Beat King,
the report said, the government is beginning to pay top attention
to the matter.
</P>
<P>
It said Health Minister Ihechukwu Madubuke has summoned the
national AIDS Control Coordinator Nasir Sani-Gwarzo and other
health officials to a meeting in Abuja this week to put finishing
touches to the policy.
</P>
<P>
The policy in view will define the roles of various arms of
governments and non-governmental organizations in AIDS control.
</P>
<P>
It will give top priority to preventive strategies, including
compulsory blood screening before any blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
While Fela is the first prominent Nigerian known to have died
of AIDS, the country's AIDS/HIV population is estimated to be as
high as two million, almost one-fifth of its total population.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his death on August 2, Fela's brother and former
Health Minister Olikoye Ransome-Kuti said they have decided to do
so so that the public and the government "will know it's a
serious issue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
