<HEADLINE> S. African National Airline Suffers from Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- South African Airways
(SAA) has lost more than 5.3 million U.S. Dollars in gold,
diamond and platinum thefts in the last six years, and one of it
has been recovered, local press Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, a heavily guarded and sealed container was
broken open and three bars of platinum, worth about 1.5 million
U.S. Dollars were stolen, the report quoted the airline's Chief
of Security Johan Piek as saying.
</P>
<P>
Piek said a highly organized international crime syndicates
must be involved because it was almost impossible to sell bars of
platinum in South Africa,
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about the lack of progress in police
investigations," senior SAA spokesman Leon Els said early this
week.
</P>
<P>
Among other incidents, a consignment of diamonds valued at
more than 319,000 U.S. Dollars was removed from an SAA aircraft
four years ago, and two years earlier platinum worth about
638,000 U.S. Dollars was stolen, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
