<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Airlines Asks for UN Approval to Fly to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian's Aeroflot airlines has
joined other world airline companies to seek the United Nations
Sanctions Committee's approval to fly medicines and medical
equipment to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Rabei Mohammed Saleh, director general of
the Iraqi Airways Co., quoted by local "Al-Jomhouria" newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
A number of world airline companies - including German, French
Dutch, British, African and Arab ones - have made similar requests
to the U.N. for permission to carry food and medical supplies, as
well as sick and old-aged people from Iraq for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said his company has received from Russia's Aeroflot a
cable saying it has made such a request and is awaiting an
approval.
</P>
<P>
Iraq affirms that the U.N. Security Council resolutions imposed
after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait do not ban civilian and
humanitarian flights to and from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It is also demanding the U.N. to allow its civilian aircraft
should to carry sick people abroad for better treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi people have been suffering greatly from the
seven-year-old U.N. sanctions due to a constant shortage of food
and medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
