<HEADLINE> Pivotals Slump on Bombay Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- After a bullish spell,
pivotals slumped on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market last
week mainly on heavy selling pressure following the reports that
the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) had deferred its
decision to review the carry-forward system.
</P>
<P>
The sensitive index that crossed the 4600 mark on Monday
dropped below the 4300 mark on Thursday on all-round selling
coupled with absence of institutional buying. The weekend rates
showed widespread losses. The trading volume dropped.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index, which spurted from the previous week
level of 4397.54 points to 4605.41 on Monday, crashed on increased
selling pressure to finish at 4320.97 with a net loss of 76.57
points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also declined from the best level of 2007.06
points to finish at 1879.22 against the previous week's level of
1914.02.
</P>
<P>
Pivotals suffered further following sustained selling pressure
by speculators due to end account considerations and the long
weekend holidays. The sharp fall was also due to the absence of
foreign institutional investors and the low activity of domestic
funds that affected the market sentiment.  
</P>
