<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Plans to Launch Islamic Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The mufti of Egypt, Sheikh Nasr
Farid Wassel, said his country is planning to launch an "Islamic
satellite" to determine with precision the Muslim lunar calendar,
the Middle East Times reported in its lastest edition.
</P>
<P>
"Studies are under way to launch in space an Egyptian Islamic
satellite to determine the start of the Muslim months," the
Egyptian weekly quoted Sheikh Wassel as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This will help put an end to disagreements which have arisen
between Arab and Islamic countries over the start of the Muslim
months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The start of the Islamic months, such as the holy month of
Ramadan, when Muslims fast from dawn to dusk, is decided by the
sighting of the new moon; and Muslim states often observe
different dates for the start of these months for lack of
consensus.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim month starts the day after the crescent is spotted
with the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Wassel said the satellite in the space would transmit to
earth pictures that would be used to determine without doubt the
new moon, which otherwise is often difficult to see because of
"natural obstacles" such as clouds.
</P>
<P>
The mufti, who is entrusted by the government to issue
religious decrees and set the start of Muslim months, said he
hoped the new satellite would be launched before Ramadan, which
should start around 31 December this year.
</P>
<P>
Appeals for donations to help finance this project, which will
cost less than 2 million U.S. dollars, will be made soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to launch its first information and
telecommunication satellite, Nilesat, next year with the help of
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
