<HEADLINE> Egyptian Interior Minister Sues Paper for Slander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister Hassan
Al-Alfi filed a libel suit Saturday against an opposition newspaper
that accused him of corruption and abuse of power, Cairo dailies
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Alfi challenged the newspaper Al Shaab to publish documents
backing up its charges that he and his associates are corrupt and
have abused their power.
</P>
<P>
It is the second case filed by Egypt's senior officials
recently against the press for slander. President Hosni Mubarak's
two sons brought a Saudi paper to court last month for publishing
a "defamatory" story of their business dealings.
</P>
<P>
Alfi told reporters earlier that "the campaign isn't the first
(against him) but the affair is dangerous because this newspaper
is the organ of the Muslim Brothers and the terrorists."
</P>
<P>
"Everything that is printed in this newspaper is a lie, and I
challenge the newspaper to publish a single document in support
(of its accusations)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Al Shaab has been accusing Alfi and some of his associates of
racketeering, nepotism and involvement in a high-profile
corruption case for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, which appears twice a week, "publishes
tendentious rumors with the goal of demoralizing the police after
their success against terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alfi's Interior Ministry is fighting a war against Islamic
militants that have staged a violent campaign since 1992 to
overthrow Egypt's incumbent secular government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
