<HEADLINE> "Parent School" for Juvenile Delinquents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A court in Fushun, a city in
northeast China, has helped juvenile delinquents break away with
their criminal past in a very special and successful way --
offering schooling for their parents.
</P>
<P>
In the district where is the court, more than 70 percent of the
juvenile cases handled by the city's Xinfu District People's Court
are considered related with family factors.
</P>
<P>
Since the opening of the "parent school" five years ago, all
the offenders sentenced by the court in the 264 juvenile cases
have "absolutely and completely broken away with" their criminal
past, according to court sources.
</P>
<P>
In addition to judges, the school invites people from the labor
union, the women's association, as well as senior educators, to
give lectures to the parents of the juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 parents have attended such classes in the school
over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
"The court has not only educated my son, but also us," said
farmer Zhang, father of a juvenile offender. "It is as well our
lack of legal and educational knowledge that has made our child a
criminal," he said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the reoccurrence of juvenile offences, the school
has extended its education coverage to local elementary and middle
schools, teaching parents in general the importance of legal
knowledge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
