<HEADLINE> Land Protection in Tibet Yields Positive Result </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The increase has come around as a result of sustained land and
forestry protection efforts of the goverment of the Tibet
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Though the region boasts a total land area of over 1.2 million
square kilometers, utility rate of land resources remains low,
largely due to a number of geographical reasons, including a high
altitude, unfavorable topography and geology, and a harsh climate.
</P>
<P>
With a policy for scientific urban planning, the regional land
administrative authorities have placed strict control on the scale
of cities and towns and are very stringent on approving land for
capital construction.
</P>
<P>
Also, the local authorities set up protection zones in 22 major
grain producing counties in the region, as a way to implement a
regulations for farm land in the region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the region launched a land reclaiming program and
successfully added some 2,000 hectares to local arable land
acreage, with the first years's crop yields sufficiently feeding
people living on the previously gravel-ridden unproductive land.
</P>
<P>
The region is pushing ahead with the reclaiming program in a
hope to lift more people out of poverty with an increasing farm
land acreage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
