<HEADLINE> Italy Beat Japan in World Volleyball Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An Italian women's volleyball
team won a historical match over Japan at the three-day Hong Kong
leg of the World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Italy won the match 15-2, 15-10, 15-6. It was their first ever
victory over Japan in any official competition.
</P>
<P>
The Italians seemed fairly easy when they took the match in
only 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Almost all the three went Italian way except for the second
during which the Japanese built a better defense mainly through
the back-row players. But the chance soon elipsed as the Italians
launnched more fierce attacks.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very, very happy for today's victory over Japan. It is
very important to Italy. Italy has a very good men's team but our
women's team was less impressive," said Italian head coach Julio
Velasco.
</P>
<P>
He recalled Italy's to Japan during the Olympic qualifying
tournament in Osaka, Japan, in April last year. "We lost 15-0 in
one of the sets. You could well see how we've improved ever
since," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We'd been very difficult in Macao where we had to play such
strong sides like China and Russia. But we had one day for
training after arriving here, which was important for us," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian coach did not think their victory over China here
yesterday meant a lot. It was only something sychological, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"World-class teams like China, Cuba and Russia are teachers in
women's volleyball. To play our teachers give our players special
strength," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese did not play well yesterday. They should have
done better," he added.
</P>
<P>
Japanese head coach Nobuchika Kuzuwa thought poor reeicing had
cost his team's chances today. "We had many problems in
receiving, which prevent them from playing to their form," he said.
</P>
<P>
There were many young and unexperienced players in the team,
who could not play cosistently during hard matches.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they could improve in a period of time, say one year,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he did not think his players would be much
affected by today's defeat. "I hope they could be confident enough
to face Italy in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked how long he thought Japan would need before
recovering to the world-class caliber as during the 60s and 70s,
he said that could be very long. "There are so many strong teams
in the world and we really lag too much behind," he admitted.
</P>
<P>
China is playig Cuba in the second match of the day and the
final one of the three-day tournament here. 
</P>
