<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's IFP Resumes Peace Talks with ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Inkatha Freedom Party
(IFP), the biggest black opposition party in South Africa, has
said it will resume peace talks with ruling African National
Congress after suspending negotiations more than one week ago.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at the weekend by IFP National
Chairman Ben Ngubane during a break in the National Council
meeting in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
IFP suspended peace talks with ANC on August 7 when it claimed
that the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) was biased
against the IFP.
</P>
<P>
TRC is a fact-finding group, which is authorized by the
government to investigate violent activities during the apartheid
era. It is also responsible for studying and approving amnesty
applications from the offenders.
</P>
<P>
The IFP's withdrawal from peace talks with ANC was sparked by
revelations to the TRC hearing in Durban by former Kwazulu Natal
Province Police Death Squad operatives, who implicated a number
of senior IFP leaders in planning political assassinations during
the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
IFP leaders initially said it would resume peace talks only
once an alternative to the TRC was created for Kwazulu Natal
Province.
</P>
<P>
Local press today quoted informed sources as saying that
rising pressure from business in the province and a perceived
loss of investor confidence had forced the IFP to rethink.
</P>
