<HEADLINE> Nepal to Set up Bank to Promote Small Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepal is preparing to set up a
Small and Cottage Industries Development Bank to promote the
country's backbone industries, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Together with some 500 entrepreneurs, the Nepal Rastra Bank,
the country's central bank, have made arrangements for the
investment capital of 81.6 million rupees (1.43 million U.S.
dollars) needed for establishing the proposed bank, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the paid-up capital of 160 million rupees (2.8 million
dollars) with the bank, which will have an authorized investment
capital of 640 million rupees (11.2 million dollars) and issued
capital of 320 million rupees (5.6 million dollars), 51 percent
will be collected from the promoters, 34 percent from the general
public, 10 percent from entrepreneurs and the remainder from the
bank employees, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
President of the proposed bank Chandra Man Shrestha stressed
the importance of setting up such a bank, saying until recently
the small and cottage enterprises in Nepal have not been able to
spring up due to the lack of capital.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 97,000 such enterprises are in a state of
bankruptcy due to lack of operating capital and market, Shrestha
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank, once established, will set up small-scale industrial
estate and provide collateral-free loans to entrepreneurs to set
up cottage and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
And it will mobilize the necessary means and resources for
setting up such enterprises in areas where small and cottage
industrial zones have not been created, the president said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also plans to implement a woman entrepreneurs program,
said the president.
</P>
<P>
Nepal Small and Cottage Industries Federation has set up women
entrepreneurship associations in 18 districts across the country
and have started skill development programs there.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program is said to be interested
in working in such programs in association with the Small and
Cottage Industries Development Bank, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
