<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Thai Deputy PM Outlines His Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Virabongsa Ramangura, the newly
appointed deputy prime minister, sees the next three months as
"most critical" for the ailing Thai economy, local newspaper "the
Nation"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a group of Thai reporters, Uirabongsa, a
former finance minister, who joined the government last Friday to
oversee financial and monetary matters, said, 'if I can make any
contribution by pushing the country one step back from teetering
off the edge of the cliff, I'll consider myself as having
accomplished enormous task."
</P>
<P>
He pledged to tackle the non-performing loans in the finance
sector, shrink the current account deficit and stabilize the
foreign exchange reserves as his top priorities in restoring
macroeconomic confidence.
</P>
<P>
Shrinking the economy to a level supported by domestic savings
and managing foreign exchange reserves are also his priorities in
an attempt to bring the macroeconomic imbalances under control.
</P>
<P>
Virabongsa, who is seen as a conservative economist, was one of
those who masterminded the baht devaluation in 1984.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that he is not a white knight who can improve
things overnight since the economic malaise is so serious that it
will take at least three years before Thais can hope to see it
take off again.
</P>
<P>
He said, 'i don't know as yet what is going to happen from now
on. But i am certain that next year things are going to get
worse.'
</P>
<P>
Local media say Thailand's economy is now at the weakest point
since the 1960s, resulting from overheated building industry,
export slowdown, non-performing loans, huge external debt burden,
high current account deficit and high import. 
</P>
</TEXT>
