<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port Imposes Congestion Surcharge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's biggest seaport
Chittagong Port imposed a temporary congestion surcharge for one
month following unsuccessful talks between port authorities and
feeder vessels operators in Singapore, port sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore-based Chittagong Feeder Trade Committee (CFTC)
has imposed the surcharge from Saturday. The surcharge was fixed
at the rate of 150 U.S. dollars for a 20-foot container and 300
dollars for a 40-foot container per day.
</P>
<P>
According to the port sources, the port will incur a loss of
several millions of dollars due to imposition of the congestion
surcharge, which will also cause a serious hindrance to the
country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The CFTC last month decided to impose the surcharge on the plea
that the Chittagong Port suffered in July a heavy congestion due
mainly to a strike by trade union bodies, heavy rainfall and
shortage of space.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from Bangladesh comprising port users and
officials held several round of talks with CFTC representatives on
Thursday, seeking a reprieve from the surcharge.
</P>
<P>
The CFTC declined to reduce the surcharge, however, it gave a
deadline of one month to remove the congestion from the port. It
would withdraw the surcharge if the port authorities could ensure
a congestion-free port within the deadline of one month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the Chittagong Port, congestion caused by the
containers was reduced considerably as the port authorities and
other relative bodies of the government took special arrangements
to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Customs, the port and the banks are working round the clock
for the last one month to remove the congestion at the port, said
the port sources.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore-based feeder operators had imposed congestion
surcharge off and on from 1992 as a result of shortage of
container handling equipment and space in container yards and
unusual strikes.
</P>
<P>
The CFIT's latest congestion surcharge was imposed in September
1995, but was lifted on July 1, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
