<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Probes Suspected Helicopter Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police is
investigating whether a group of Sri Lankan millionaire
businessmen were trying to purchase eight MI-24 helicopters for
the Tamil rebels who are fighting with government troops, police
sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
Three businessmen were arrested by the police and have been
remanded till August 20, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Investigations made by detectives reportedly revealed that a
Sri Lankan businessman had arrived in the Ukraine to place an
order for the purchase of eight MI helicopters, they said.
</P>
<P>
Since there was no such order from the Ministry of Defense or
the Sri Lankan Air Force in Colombo, it was suspected that the
clandestine purchase was being made for the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The sources added that investigations also revealed that the
group of three businessmen were to receive the equivalent of 1
million U.S. dollars as commissions for each helicopter from the
suppliers.  
</P>
