<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of New Vice President of India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Andhra Pradesh Governor
Krishan Kant was elected vice-president of India here Saturday
evening by members of both houses of parliament and he is expected
to be sworn in on August 21.
</P>
<P>
Krishan Kant, 70, was born on February 28, 1927, at Kot
Mohammed Khan village in Amritar District of Punjab in
northwestern India in a family of freedom fighters. He took an
active part in the Quit India Movement of 1942 when he was a
student in Lahore (now in Pakistan) and was arrested along with
members of his family. His father, Lala Achint Ram, was a member
of the Constituent Assembly and later a member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
He began his political career as a member of the Congress and
later was expelled from the Congress for opposing the infamous
emergency declared by Indira Gandhi in 1975. With former prime
minister Chandra Shekhar and Mohan Dharia, he had formed the
celebrated group of "Young Turks" and often espoused causes which
were not always to the liking of the party leadership.
</P>
<P>
He was the first to raise the question of criminalisation of
politics and he is strongly against corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Krishan Kant is a childhood friend of Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral. Both went to school and college together and
participated in the freedom struggle as student leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank's Education Program Helps Chinese Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An education program designated
to help children in China's poor areas, launched by the World
Bank, had financed 25,400 children and built 94 schools in
northwest China's Qinghai Province since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The program, with 100 million US dollars in loans, targets
children in China's 124 poorest counties in seven provinces.
</P>
<P>
The sum for Qinghai totals eight million US dollars, according
to local officials. The provincial government has allocated 33.2
million yuan (about 4.15 million US dollars) to support the
program.
</P>
<P>
The money provided thus far has been used to build 94 schools,
train 1,600 educational personnel, and buy 15,000 desks and
chairs. An additional 73 schools are expected to be created in
1997.
</P>
<P>
When the program ends in 2001, the enrollment rate of children
at school age is expected to stand at 71.2 percent, compared to
the present 57.8 percent in the province, officials revealed.
</P>
