<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Groups to Watch Court Case Involving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Observers from two
international human rights groups will be present to monitor
Monday's court case between opposition Workers' Party chief J.B.
Jeyaretnam and 11 ruling People's Action Party (PAP) leaders,
including Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew, the Straits Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that International Commission of Jurists and
Amnesty International are sending representatives to the hearing
scheduled to last 12 days.
</P>
<P>
Jeyaretnam is now facing eight lawsuits for the remarks he made
at a Workers' Party election campaign rally on January 1, this
year, the eve of polling day in the last general election.
</P>
<P>
He told the rally that his Workers' Party team-mate in the
Cheng San Group Representative Constituency (GRC), lawyer Tang
Liang Hong, had just placed before him two reports the latter made
to the police against Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and his team.
</P>
<P>
The PAP leaders, including Prime Minister Goh and Senior
Minister Lee, are claiming that the words Jeyaretnam used implied
that they had conspired to commit criminal defamation against Mr.
Tang by labeling him an anti-Christian, anti-English educated
Chinese chauvinist.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times said that a spokesman for the Ministry of
Information and the Arts, when asked to comment on the presence of
these observers, said on Saturday that the Ministry hopes "they
will stay and monitor carefully the case from beginning to end and
give a faithful report of how the rule of law is upheld in
Singapore."
</P>
<P>
The Times of London had reported last Wednesday that senior
legal observers from Australia and Mr. Paul Bentley, an Ontario
judge representing Amnesty International, would be in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
Jeyaretnam, who is represented by Queen's Counsel George
Carman, was quoted as saying that Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew,
one of the PAP leaders suing Jeyaretnam, was "terrified of being
questioned by Mr. Carman."
</P>
<P>
Responding to this, Lee Kuan Yew's press secretary Madam Yeong
Yoon Ying said, according to the Straits Times report, "Mr. Lee is
always a little nervous when he goes to court. After reading of
Mr. Carman's formidable reputation as a terrifying cross-examiner,
Mr. Lee is anxious not to let down his own counsel. Mr. Lee does
not have a Queen's Counsel. But he has been reassured by his
Senior Counsel Davinder Singh that answering questions truthfully
will be good enough."
</P>
<P>
An Amnesty International statement said last Friday that it
would monitor the hearing as it was concerned over reports that
the Singapore Government used civil defamation suits against
political opponents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
