<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspection To Improve Accounting Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- China's national accounting
association said it wants to remould the country's 6,700
accounting firms into a team of "economic policemen".
</P>
<P>
By the end of the campaign, which began this month and ends in
1998, accounting firms are expected to enhance their quality to
play their role more properly and effectively in economic
activities which need their participation, today's "China Daily"
quoted Ding Pingzhun as saying, who is secretary-general of the
Chinese Institute of Certified Public Accountants (CICPA).
</P>
<P>
Accounting firms are required to conduct self-inspection before
CICPA's provincial branches and CICPA itself will inspect the
firms next year.
</P>
<P>
Firms which do not meet standards or break rules will be
stripped of licenses or be ordered to improve, Ding said.
</P>
<P>
He said the most urgent demand for improvement of Chinese CPAs
comes from the stock market, where some irregular or fraudulent
auditing reports have lead to confusion among investors and have
constituted malpractice by some listed companies.
</P>
<P>
China's stock market, with over 600 listed companies at
present, is expanding very fast.
</P>
<P>
The significance for the accounting industry's improvement is
underscored by the central government's decision that accounting
reports of all big State enterprises must be audited by CPAs.
</P>
<P>
Ding said one of the major goals of the industry overhaul is to
sever accounting firms' connections with government agencies or
other enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Under the control of government offices, it is impossible for
the accounting firms to be independent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
