<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Cultural News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are news
briefs about cultural events in Latin America in the last few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- An indigenous handicraft fair was opened in
Buenos Aires and more than 100 ethnic craftsmen from across the
country will produce their works during the three-week show.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Fair of the Sun, with the slogan "Natural and
Hand-Made," shows diverse culture of the country's indigenous
communities, including the Toba, Pilaga, Chane, Wichi, Guarani,
and Kolla ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Three Brazilian films were selected for the Toronto
International Film Festival to be held on September 4, the local
press reported. They are "The Oister and the Wind", "Perfumed
Dance", and "Matadores".
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A concert to remember Argentine guerrilla leader
Ernesto "Che" Guevara will be held in Santiago on September 28,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Artists to take part in the concert include Cuba's Silvio
Rodriguez, Carmen Prieto, Francisco Sazo, Brazil's Chico Buarque,
Argentina's Mercedes Sosa and Uruguay's Daniel Viglietti. A
similar concert will be held in Buenos Aires on October 8.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan Pro Opera Society will give three
performances of "Turandot," an unfinished opera of Italian
composer Giacomo Puccini, this month.
</P>
<P>
The main roles will be played by Uruguay's Sopranos Graciela
Zographos, Argentina's Adelaida Negri and Ana Maria Gonzalez from
Spain. The Brazilian Symphonic Orchestra of Porto Alegre will
participate in the performance.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Third International Theater Festival of
Nicaragua was opened on August 16. Eleven national groups and
players from Honduras, Costa Rica, and France will give
performances during the festival, which will end on August 23.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran group, "Teatro Bambu," will present "Only for
Children," a theme dedicated this year to children and youth.
</P>
