<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boon or Bane of Nation's Economy? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- There are two diametrically
different opinions in China towards the use of foreign direct
investment (FDI): One favors it, the other disfavors it.
</P>
<P>
People against FDI argue it could crush the national industry
or economic autonomy. But some of these opinions have gone beyond
the pure economic sense, according to an article carried on
today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Those skeptical people fear that foreign investors attempt to
monopolize technology. In other words, China has yet to import
state-of-the-art technology from foreign partners, Liu Su from the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, noted in the
second of a series of articles to clear fears about FDI in China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors squeeze domestic counterparts out of the
market, and state assets are lost as they are under-valued in
forming joint ventures with foreign partners, according to the
skepticists.
</P>
<P>
Hence they propose that there should be a limit to FDI, of
which China has had enough, the article said.
</P>
<P>
If exports go well, China should import more technology and
equipment mainly with export income instead of FDI.
</P>
<P>
They also suggest that China should prefer foreign loans to FDI
to avert possible threats to economic autonomy, Liu observed.
</P>
<P>
China should encourage smaller investors and discourage larger
ones, like trans-national companies which may harm Chinese
national industry and economic safety, the skepticists say.
</P>
<P>
However, people who favor FDI argue that with increased
international division of labor, globalization has come to mark
the world economy. There's no 100 percent "national" industry
independent of the global community.
</P>
<P>
Any policy based on "national industry" in a narrow sense will
thus erode or erase national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
They say that foreign-funded firms should not be viewed as
enemies of the national economy. At present, China's mainland
investors hold 30 percent of joint venture capital. Of the capital
held by overseas investors, 60 percent are from Hong Kong, Taiwan
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary and amenable to use FDI in sectors such as
automobiles and aircraft, where China lacks advanced technologies
for quick development, they add.
</P>
<P>
Poor management is the main reason why State assets are lost,
they point out, saying that FDI is not to blame for the market
failure of some domestic brands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Adopt Mandatory, Free Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican children aged five
to seven will be obliged to go to school and they will get free
education in 1998, the Education Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government will also raise the public education
budget next year from 4.3 percent of the gross domestic product to
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The measure, guaranteeing education to some 80,000 Costa Rican
children, is a step toward universal education which provides
equal opportunities to all Costa Rican children, Education
Minister Eduardo Doryan said.
</P>
<P>
The project, approved by the Legislative Assembly and President
Jose Maria Figuers, will provide 4,000 schools and colleges across
the country with about 180 million U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the increased education spending will help Costa
Rica to catch up with developed countries in education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
