<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snowstorm Kills Eight Children in Southern Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Recent snowfalls in the southern
mountain ranges of Peru have left eight children dead and some
20,000 inhabitants stranded, the authorities said today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 19 towns in the high Andean zones of the department
of Arequipa were isolated by snow and urgent aid was needed,
Cailloma Mayor Carlos Pichas told a local radio station.
</P>
<P>
"Snow has been falling since August 7, leaving a deep mantle
over the roads, and we cannot communicate or travel, and many
children are in peril and assistance is needed urgently," said the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
Domestic animals were dying in their stalls because the grass
was covered by ice and snow, said inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
The mayor requested blankets and medicines for the affected
population.
</P>
<P>
Pichas asked the air force to bring in the aid by helicopters
and to fly over the zone to evaluate the situation of these
townships.
</P>
<P>
The Ayacucho department, which lies northeast of Arequipa, is
also affected. In the department, hundreds of lams have died
because of the cold and lack of fodder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
