<HEADLINE> Economist: 1997 Inflation Less Than 2% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- China should take advantage of a
low inflation rate to accelerate economic restructuring, a senior
official said last week.
</P>
<P>
National retail prices inched up 1.6 percent between January
and July, the lowest since the mid-1980s, said today's Business
Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist and spokesman of the State
Statistics Bureau (SSB), predicted the year-end inflation rate at
less than two percent, far below the projected six percent.
</P>
<P>
"We should take this rare opportunity to speed up the reform of
State-owned firms, the housing system, as well as investment and
price structures," Qiu noted.
</P>
<P>
State-owned firms face less pressure to pare their redundant
labor force during periods of low inflation, he explained.
</P>
<P>
A low inflation rate also forces manufacturers to cut prices to
survive fierce market competition, hence a need for them to change
their unprofitable production mix.
</P>
<P>
As for housing reform, Qiu said it is amenable to raise both
employees' salaries and housing rents, while increasing bank loans
to enhance the public's home-purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Qiu said accelerated housing reform would help recoup nearly
100 billion yuan ($12 billion) locked in 50 million sq.m. of
unsold apartments across the country.
</P>
<P>
Other infrastructures like high ways and water conservancy
projects for agriculture could also get more input, he added.
</P>
<P>
China's inflation rate soared to 21.7 percent in 1994 but
continued decreasing until now.
</P>
<P>
Qiu suggested the government focus more on stabilizing than on
simply cutting prices.
</P>
<P>
The current low inflation is a natural result of a transition
from an overheated economy to a moderate one. "It's remarkable for
China to bring down its double-digit inflation rate to 1.6 percent
in only three years, " Qiu noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
