<DOCNO> XIE19970817.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deficits to be Cut by $1.2 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 17 (Xinhua) -- China is likely to slash
deficits by nearly 10 billion yuan ($1.2 billion) this fiscal
year, according to a report from the State Information Center
(SIC).
</P>
<P>
The forecast would bring hope to financial authorities, who are
striving to "invigorate China's financial situation" and balance
revenue and expenditures by the end of the century, said today's
Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
However, some experts believed the extra expenditures might
offset the increase in the fiscal incomes.
</P>
<P>
The SIC report estimated that this year's fiscal revenue would
grow 17 percent to 861.9 billion yuan ($103.8 billion).
</P>
<P>
Fiscal spending would rise 14.7 percent to 907.4 billion yuan
($109 billion), cutting total deficits to 45.5 billion yuan ($5.48
billion) from the present 57 billion yuan ($6.8 billion ).
</P>
<P>
The ratio of fiscal revenue to GDP is expected to crawl from
11.3 percent to 11.6 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, Su Ming, deputy director of the Research Institute of
Fiscal Science under the Ministry of Finance, predicted that the
central government still faces an uphill battle to balance the
fiscal income and spending by 2000.
</P>
<P>
He urged the financial authorities to tighten control over tax
collection and strengthen the central government's power in
manoeuvring the available money resources.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance announced last month that fiscal
revenue grew 29.9 percent in the first half of the year, reaching
390.1 billion yuan ($47 billion).
</P>
<P>
Expenditures rose 21.1 percent to 351.2 billion yuan ($42.3
billion), resulting in a surplus of 38.8 billion yuan ($4.6
billion).
</P>
<P>
The SIC report said that the increase of the stamp tax for
stock trading, personal income tax revenue and customs duties has
contributed to the growth of fiscal revenue. Meanwhile, some
State-owned enterprises witnessed better performance in the first
half of the year, generating more income taxes and less
governmental subsidies to money-losing firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
