<HEADLINE> Berger: Regular High-Level Exchanges With China Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. National Security
Advisor Samuel Berger said here today that it is extremely
important for the U.S. to have regular high-level talks with
Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's extremely important that we have regular
high-level exchanges with the Chinese leadership and the American
leadership," he told CNN's Evans &AMP; Novak program.
</P>
<P>
Berger returned earlier this week from a three-day trip to
China to prepare for a landmark visit of Chinese President Jiang
Zemin to Washington this fall.
</P>
<P>
Berger said the United States has to engage with China rather
than contain it.
</P>
<P>
"This (China) is a quarter of the world's people. This is an
enormous country. And how they develop, what direction they take,
has an enormous impact on the next generation. And so we have to
engage with them."
</P>
<P>
"We have enormous stake in the direction in which China
evolves," he added.
</P>
<P>
Berger, who met Jiang and other senior Chinese officials
during his trip, believed that the U.S. and China have common
interests in the Korean Peninsula, Cambodia and arms control. In
these areas "we can work together," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He recognized that the two countries still disagree on human
rights, trade and weapons sales.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the human rights issue is not the
only issue in the relationship. "There are broad interests here,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"So having engagement ... means a vehicle for trying to expand
cooperation and deal with problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
Berger is seen as a fast-rising star in President Bill
Clinton's plan for a second-term legacy of success on the
international stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
