<HEADLINE> Chile Asks U.S. Fairness in Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Defense Minister
Edmundo Perez Yoma said the United States policy for South America
must be the same for all the countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister told "El Mercurio" in an exclusive interview
published today that Chile has not requested any special privilege
over other countries of the region because it considers that must
not be done.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last Wednesday
that Washington would likely choose Argentina as its close
military ally outside the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), adding that the status is open to other countries,
including Chile.
</P>
<P>
Perez said that it is not convenient to establish differences
in the southern half of South America, which has known how to
solve its historical conflicts and preserved the peace for almost
one century.
</P>
<P>
He said the present situation does not affect the relations
between Chile and Argentina, and that "what we want with Argentina
is to continue on the same road we started."
</P>
<P>
"We want to deepen our relations and believe that it would be
good to analyze these measures together."
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Washington said the granting of the status to
Argentina is expected to be announced by U.S. President Bill
Clinton when he visits Argentina in October.
</P>
<P>
Under the Foreign Assistance Act of 1961, the U.S. president
has the right to designate close military allies, a status that
does not require U.S. help in case of attacks, but allows the
allies to buy excess weapons from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Countries already designated as close non-NATO U.S. allies are
Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Japan and South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
