<HEADLINE> Specialists Say "El Nino" Will Be Worst of the Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Central American meteorologists
said the "El Nino" climate phenomenon of this season will be the
worst of the century for the region, where it will cause damage to
agriculture, drinking water supply, and power generation.
</P>
<P>
"El Nino" causes droughts in the Pacific watershed of Central
America from May to November, while in the Atlantic side the rains
increase, said Eladio Zarate, executive secretary of the Regional
committee of Hydraulic Resources.
</P>
<P>
Zarate was attending the 31st Meeting of Meteorological
Services Directors of Central America this week in San Salvador.
</P>
<P>
The government agencies in the region in charge of agriculture
and animal husbandry, drinking water supply and power generation
are adopting preventive measures in anticipation of the biggest
repercussions of El Nino, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
