<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Swedish Opposition to Olympic Bid Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A poll commissioned by the
Stockholm Olympic Bidding Committee showed that Swedish opposition
to Stockholm's bid to host the 2004 Olympic Games has decreased.
</P>
<P>
A report published on Saturday said that opposition has fallen
from 41 percent in May to 28 percent in August according to a poll
of 1,000 Swedes over the age of 15 questioned August 12-14.
</P>
<P>
"We set a goal to have less than 30 percent of Swedes opposed
to the project, and we have now reached that," Olympic bid company
president Goeran Laangsved said.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, a total of 49 percent are in favour of
the Games, unchanged from the May survey, while the number of
undecided grew from seven to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Support is strongest among people aged 15-29, where 66 percent
support the bid.
</P>
<P>
Other polls have indicated that almost 77 percent of Swedes are
in favour of the Games if the cash does not have to come out of
the Swedish budget, according to Laangsved.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish capital is competing against Athens, Rome, Buenos
Aires and Cape Town to host the Games. The host city will be
announced on September 5 in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
