<HEADLINE> Herons Return to Nature after Being Saved by Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Zoo workers in Zhengzhou, the
capital of China's Henan Province, freed 30 herons last week.
</P>
<P>
The birds had been saved by Zhengzhou residents when they fell
from their nests in trees because of wounds or illness. And, local
police seized others being sold on the black market or being
smuggled out of the area.
</P>
<P>
Veterinarians and other zoo staff have taken good care of the
herons, some of which were still fledglings. They fed the birds
small fish and after three months' care, they had become healthy
again.
</P>
<P>
Zhengzhou is called the "green city" by its residents because
of the tall green trees that line its streets. Many herons have
made their nests on those trees in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The local people have developed a better sense of caring for
wildlife, according to an official with the provincial wild animal
protection office, who noted that about 10,000 wild animals are
saved by local people yearly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
