of Trinidad and Tobago into second place over 200m in a time of
19.93.
</P>
<P>
World 800m champion and world record holder Wilson Kipketer
hardly broke sweat in winning his race.
</P>
<P>
Kenya-born Dane Kipketer, who smashed the world record in
Zurich just three days ago with 1:41.24, ran a still impressive
1:42.77 with Kenyans Patrick Konchellah and Hezekiel Sepend second
and third.
</P>
<P>
American Bryan Bronson beat out recently-crowned world 400m
hurdles champion Stephane Diagana of France by a meter in the
fastest time in the world this year of 47.64 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Falilat Ogunkoya, who finished fifth at the World
Championships, won the event in 49.48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
But in the women's javelin, world champion Trine Hattestad of
Norway could only finish second to Oksana Ovshinnikova of Russia,
who threw 68.38m.
</P>
<P>
World champions Allen Johnson and Carla Sacramento of the
United States kept their forms at the meet, with Johnson winning
the 100m hurdles in 13.18 and Sacramento taking the women's 1,500m
at 4:01.86. 
