<HEADLINE> Muslim Refugees Return to Croat-Controlled Jajce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Muslim refugees today
began returning to the Croat-controlled Jajce area in central
Bosnia in what is the test case of the on-and-off relations
between the two ethnic partners.
</P>
<P>
The return was in line with an agreement reached Wednesday
between Muslims and Croat officials, allowing 474 families of
displaced Muslims to return their homes to villages around the
town of Jajce.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, some 100 refugees arrived at the village
of Kruscica today from the Muslim-controlled town of Travnik and
many more were expected to go back to the villages of Lendici,
Lucici, Divicani and Sibenica next week.
</P>
<P>
The return was reported as free of any incident by the NATO-led
peacekeeping forces which were patroling the roads to monitor the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, more than 500 Muslim refugees who had just
returned to their homes in the Jajce area were forced to flee
again by Croat protesters who claimed that the return was not
agreed upon in advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
